  "chunk_index": 27,
  "summary": "Huestis informs Colonel Finney that although the motive for the murder remains unknown, he believes witnesses will likely fall silent once they realize they have revealed too much. Huestis intends to question Lindström to investigate potential animosity between her and Mrs. Aigle, as well as Philip Darlant, a paralyzed man whom Huestis suspects may have witnessed something significant.\n\nMeanwhile, Mickey takes Tina for a walk from her library to a pavilion by a riverbank to escape the cold. During the walk, Mickey expresses feelings of displacement and restlessness, noting that he does not feel he belongs in his current environment. He mentions he has been offered a job managing car transport for an oil company in the Persian Gulf. A tense conversation follows regarding Mickey's biological mother. Tina expresses gratitude to Mrs. Aigle for providing her with a secure home and identity, whereas Mickey harbors resentment toward his upbringing and the luxury provided. Tina suggests that Mickey's anger toward Mrs. Aigle is actually displaced hatred for his biological mother, positing that if Mickey killed Mrs. Aigle, he was attempting to kill the memory of his own mother. Mickey denies involvement in the murder, claiming he was giving a customer a test drive near Moor Road and Mingjing Mountain at the time of the crime. The conversation shifts when Tina points out two figures on the riverbank below, whom Mickey identifies as Hurst and her doctor friend.",
